Chrysanthemum coronarium var. coronarium

   [4524.jpg]
    Authority   L.
      Family    Magnoliopsida:Asteridae:Asterales:Compositae
     Synonyms
   Common names
      Editor
   Ecocrop code 4524

   Notes
   BRIEF DESCRIPTION An erect, densely leafy, branched herb reaching 20-60
   cm in height in the vegetative stage and 90-120 cm when flowering. It
   has heads of yellow flowers. USES Young leaves and seedlings are used
   as a vegetable and the plant is used as an ornamental. The small-leaf
   types have a very strong taste and are eaten cooked or fried, often
   together with other vegetables in soups. The large-leaf types can in
   addition be eaten raw in salads. The flowers are also edible, usually
   petals are used, fresh or dried, as a garnish or to brew a tea. The
   plant also has medicinal properties. It is a possible agroforestry
   species. GROWING PERIOD Annual. Seedlings can be harvested 4-5 weeks
   from sowing when they are 5-10 cm tall, or plants can be harvested when
   they are more mature, after 6-8 weeks at a height of 15-25 cm. COMMON
   NAMES Garland chrysanthemum, Spring chrysanthemum, Crown daisy, Tangho,
   Chop suey green, Japanese green, Chrysantheme des jardins, Tango,
   Saruni walanda, Tang'oo, Phaktang-o, Phakkhikhwai. FURTHER INF Garland
   chrysanthemum is native of the Mediterranean region and distributed
   throughout Europe, northern Africe, and Asia. It is shade tolerant. In
   seed production yields vary from 1.3-2 t/ha.

   Sources
   Siemonsma J 1993 pp 140-142 [TEMP, KTMP, PHO, LIG, RAIN, DRA, TEXT]
   Roecklein J 1987 pp 489 [USE]
   Duke J 1975 pp 11 [PH, RAIN, TEMP]

